05426nam a22009135i 9780271092584DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710925847 a10.1515/97802710925842doi  a(DE-B1597)651523  a(OCoLC)1380732266  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aART0151002bisacsh1 aBradstreet, Christina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScented Visions :bSmell in Art, 1850-1914 /cChristina Bradstreet. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (290 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives on Sensory History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Seeing Smell -- t1. The Fallen Angel -- t2. Art and Stench -- t3. Picturing Perfume -- t4. Smelling Pictures -- tPart II: Decoding Smell -- t5. Scent, Memory, Visions -- t6. Scent and Soul -- t7. The Erotics of Scent -- t8. Death by Perfume -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSmell loomed large in cultural discourse in the late nineteenth century, thanks to the midcentury fear of miasma, the drive for sanitation reform, and the rise in artificial perfumery. Meanwhile, the science of olfaction remained largely mysterious, prompting an impulse to “see smell” and inspiring some artists to picture scent in order to better know and control it. This book recovers the substantive role of the olfactory in Pre-Raphaelite art and Aestheticism.Christina Bradstreet examines the iconography and symbolism of scent in nineteenth-century art and visual culture. Fragrant imagery in the work of John Everett Millais, Dante Gabriel Rossetti, Simeon Solomon, George Frederic Watts, Edward Burne-Jones, and others set the trend for the preoccupation with scent that informed swaths of British, European, and American art and design. Bradstreet’s rich analyses of paintings, perfume posters, and other works of visual culture demonstrate how artworks mirrored the “period nose” and intersected with the most clamorous debates of the day, including evolution, civilization, race, urban morality, mental health, faith, and the “woman question.”Beautifully illustrated and grounded in current practices in sensory history, Scented Visions presents both fresh readings of major works of art and a deeper understanding of the cultural history of nineteenth-century scent.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt for art's sake (Movement). 0aArt, Moderny19th century. 0aArt, Moderny20th century. 0aOdors in artxHistoryy19th century. 0aOdors in artxHistoryy20th century. 0aPre-Raphaelitism. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh  aAestheticism.  aCultural history of smell.  aDecadence.  aGeorge Frederick Watts.  aJohn Singer Sargent.  aMiasma.  aMillais.  aNineteenth-century painting.  aOdor / Odour.  aOlfactory.  aPerfume.  aPre-Raphaelitism.  aRossetti.  aScent.  aSensory history.  aSimeon Solomon.  aSmell.  aSynaesthesia.  aVictorian art .  aVictorian painting.  aVictorian studies.  aWaterhouse.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2022z9783110992809oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishz978311099281608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z